(1, 'Apo', '1.jpg', 'Mount Apo is the highest mountain in the Philippines, located on the island of Mindanao. With an elevation of approximately 2,954 meters (9,692 feet), it is a popular destination for tourists and adventurers alike. Mount Apo is covered with tropical forests and has a hot spring at its summit, making it an attractive destination for relaxation and nature exploration.', 'Mount Apo holds cultural and historical significance for indigenous peoples of the Philippines, especially the Lumad communities. It is often regarded as a sacred mountain and is revered by local communities.', 'Trekking Mount Apo requires basic trekking skills and good preparation for the mountain environment. Travelers need to be able to navigate through challenging mountain trails and ensure safety in harsh weather conditions.', '<iframe src=\"https://www.google.com/maps/embed?pb=!1m18!1m12!1m3!1d15840.739995909904!2d125.2606966618733!3d6.987477186631136!2m3!1f0!2f0!3f0!3m2!1i1024!2i768!4f13.1!3m3!1m2!1s0x32f9011b1d616fe9%3A0x83086f84a0a9e915!2zTsO6aSBBcG8!5e0!3m2!1svi!2s!4v1708952428922!5m2!1svi!2s\" width=\"600\" height=\"450\" style=\"border:0;\" allowfullscreen=\"\" loading=\"lazy\" referrerpolicy=\"no-referrer-when-downgrade\"></iframe>', 'Located in the south of Mindanao Island, Philippines.', 'The area surrounding Mount Apo provides ideal stopping points for those seeking refuge and relaxation in nature. There are camping grounds and accommodations available to serve travelers.', 'Hazards when trekking Mount Apo include risks from harsh weather conditions, rugged terrain, and altitude. Additionally, there are risks from rockslides and climate factors. Thorough preparation and adherence to safety guidelines are crucial to ensure safety during the trek.', 0),
(2, 'Mera Peak', '1.jpg', 'Conquer the highest trekking peak in Nepal and enjoy epic views of the world’s highest mountains, including mighty Everest itself.\r\nMera Peak is a mountain in the Mahalangur section, Barun sub-section of the Himalaya and administratively in Nepal\'s Sagarmatha Zone, Sankhuwasabha. At 6,476 metres (21,247 ft) it is classified as a trekking peak. It contains three main summits: Mera North, 6,476 metres (21,247 ft); Mera Central, 6,461 metres (21,198 ft); and Mera South, 6,065 metres (19,898 ft), as well as a smaller \"\"trekking summit\"\", visible as a distinct summit from the south but not marked on most maps of the region.', 'The height of Mera is often given as The region was first explored extensively by British expeditions in the early 50s before and after the ascent of Everest. Members of those teams included Edmund Hillary, Tenzing Norgay, Eric Shipton and George Lowe.\r\n\r\nThe first ascent of Mera Central was on May 20, 1953 by Col. Jimmy Roberts and Sen Tenzing (who was known by the nickname The Foreign Sportsman). Roberts was heavily involved in establishing the trekking industry in Nepal in the early 1960s. He was posthumously awarded the \"Sagarmatha (Everest) National Award\" by the government in May 2005.\r\n\r\nMera North is believed to have first been climbed by the French climbers Marcel Jolly, G. Baus and L. Honills in 1975,though some sources state that it was climbed on 29 October 1973 and the climbers included L. Limarques, Ang Lhakpa and two other Sherpas.\r\n\r\nIn 1986 Mal Duff and Ian Tattersall made the first ascent of the south west pillar. The route is approximately 1,800 metres (5,900 ft) in length and graded at ED inf. The approach to the base of the pillar is extremely exposed to serac fall.\r\n\r\nIn September 2017, Hari Budha Magar summited Mera Peak, in doing so he became the first ever double above-knee amputee to climb a mountain over 6,000m in altitude.', '\"Trekking the Mera Peak Requires Mountain Climbing Skills.\r\n\r\nMount Mera demands fewer mountain climbing skills compared to other locations in the region. However, its significant height and extended trekking days require maintaining adequate hydration and a steady, controlled pace.\r\n\r\nThe altitude not only affects physical stamina but also influences your overall metabolism, resulting in decreased appetite and altered sleep patterns. To ensure optimal performance during the ascent, it\'s essential to adjust your diet and increase water intake.\r\n\r\nCommon challenges that may hinder successful completion of the journey include fatigue, muscle energy depletion, digestive issues, and altitude sickness. Therefore, maintaining proper nutrition, ample rest, and adequate hydration are crucial for conquering this trek.\"', '<iframe src=\"https://www.google.com/maps/embed?pb=!1m18!1m12!1m3!1d14129.070241620797!2d86.8574809497422!3d27.709024068901776!2m3!1f0!2f0!3f0!3m2!1i1024!2i768!4f13.1!3m3!1m2!1s0x39e902c6aed66d65%3A0xb648f96ab2dc0828!2sMera%20Peak!5e0!3m2!1sen!2s!4v1708607282627!5m2!1sen!2s\" width=\"600\" height=\"450\" style=\"border:0;\" allowfullscreen=\"\" loading=\"lazy\" referrerpolicy=\"no-referrer-when-downgrade\"></iframe>', 'Hinku Valley, Nepal', '\"On the journey to conquer Mera Peak, we will stay in lodges/homestays operated by local families, or you can choose to use outdoor camping tents if desired. Each lodge has a communal area with a shared kitchen where everyone can eat and chat with fellow trekkers. The sleeping quarters are arranged with twin beds, mattresses, blankets, and pillows.\r\n\r\nAdditionally, the menu at these lodges is diverse, blending local Sherpa cuisine with Western recipes. You can order meat sandwiches and french fries in Lukla. However, as you reach Mera, you\'ll find most lodges serving Dal Bhat or Momos, as this area is not as developed as other regions in the area. Still, you can find everything from flashlights to energy bars available at homestays and stores along the trekking route.\r\n\r\nFor the 2 summit days, you will spend the night in a tent with a capacity for two people. It\'s recommended to bring a four-season sleeping bag and a sleeping pad to keep your body warm when the night falls.\"', '\"Lukla serves as the starting point for every journey to the Himalayas, featuring the main hospital and airport for evacuating injured individuals. Depending on weather conditions and visibility, the support center may deploy helicopters to certain areas in Mera. In emergencies, the group and the guide will coordinate to transfer the injured to the nearest safe location and then assess the feasibility of evacuation. Alternatively, you can hire someone to descend to lower altitudes at a cost of $150 per day.\r\n\r\nIf your travel insurance includes helicopter evacuation coverage, you can contact the insurance company to request emergency services.\"', 0),
(3, 'Jebel Um Shomer', '1.jpg', 'Follow ancient trails with Bedouin nomads for a wild expedition through the valleys and mountains of the Sinai Peninsula', 'A sharp, jagged summit with an almost Alpine feel, Jebel Um Shomer towers 2587m over a wilderness of rugged hills and winding wadis. Thunder was once said to echo around its summit, leading some to suggest it was the real Mount Sinai of The Bible. One legend has it an immortal maiden - whose hair flowed in rich waves down her back - lived in its high crags, bewitching wayfarers with enchanting song before disappearing forever when a hunter tried to catch her. Up until the 19th century, Jebel Um Shomer was reckoned to be the Sinai\'s highest mountain and it became a prestigious target for European mountaineers, all of whom wanted to be the first to reach the top. Swiss explorer J. L Burckhardt - the first European to see Petra - attempted an ascent in the early 19th century, but turned back before the steep summit crags. Englishmen T.E Yorke and T. J Prout - whose names remain carved into a summit boulder - made the first recorded summit climb in 1862. In the following decades, it was conclusively shown Jebel Um Shomer was the Sinai\'s second highest mountain after Jebel Katherina. From the top of Jebel Um Shomer, hikers can gaze over the Gulf of Suez to the high summits of mainland Egypt and Africa. Sometimes in clear weather the Hejaz mountains of Arabia are visible too. Jebel Um Shomer gives an excellent mountain adventure, with steep scrambling almost all the way to the summit.', 'When climbing Jebel Um Shomer, a mountain located in Saudi Arabia, several skills are essential to ensure a safe and successful ascent. These skills include:\r\n\r\nPhysical Fitness: Climbing Jebel Um Shomer requires a good level of physical fitness. Endurance, strength, and cardiovascular fitness are essential for tackling the steep and rugged terrain.\r\n\r\nRock Climbing Skills: As Jebel Um Shomer involves scrambling over rocky terrain, basic rock climbing skills are necessary. This includes techniques for ascending steep slopes, navigating rocky obstacles, and using climbing equipment such as ropes, harnesses, and carabiners.\r\n\r\nRoute Finding: Familiarity with route finding techniques is crucial for navigating the mountain\'s complex terrain. Knowledge of map reading, GPS navigation, and understanding topographic maps will help climbers stay on course and avoid getting lost.\r\n\r\nSafety Protocols: Understanding safety protocols and practicing risk management is vital for mountain climbing. This includes knowledge of how to assess and mitigate hazards such as rockfall, avalanches, and adverse weather conditions.\r\n\r\nAltitude Acclimatization: Jebel Um Shomer reaches heights of over 2,000 meters (6,561 feet), so climbers should be prepared for altitude-related challenges. Acclimatization techniques, such as gradual ascent and staying hydrated, can help prevent altitude sickness and ensure a safe climb.\r\n\r\nFirst Aid Skills: Basic first aid knowledge is essential for addressing common injuries and medical emergencies that may occur during the climb. This includes treating wounds, fractures, altitude sickness, and hypothermia.\r\n\r\nTeamwork and Communication: Climbing Jebel Um Shomer often involves teamwork, so effective communication skills and the ability to work collaboratively with climbing partners are important. Clear communication helps ensure everyone\'s safety and facilitates problem-solving in challenging situations.\r\n\r\nEnvironmental Awareness: Practicing Leave No Trace principles and respecting the natural environment is essential for preserving the beauty and integrity of Jebel Um Shomer. Minimizing impact on the ecosystem and adhering to local regulations help sustain the mountain\'s ecosystem for future generations.\r\n\r\nBy honing these skills and preparing adequately, climbers can embark on a safe and enjoyable adventure to conquer Jebel Um Shomer.\"', '<iframe src=\"https://www.google.com/maps/embed?pb=!1m18!1m12!1m3!1d14043.517116543124!2d33.904978050153204!3d28.362499163008582!2m3!1f0!2f0!3f0!3m2!1i1024!2i768!4f13.1!3m3!1m2!1s0x14537dba75afdb83%3A0x59044524169158bd!2sJabal%20Umm%20Sh%C5%ABmar!5e0!3m2!1sen!2s!4v1708607318749!5m2!1sen!2s\" width=\"600\" height=\"450\" style=\"border:0;\" allowfullscreen=\"\" loading=\"lazy\" referrerpolicy=\"no-referrer-when-downgrade\"></iframe>', 'Jebel Um Shomer is in the territory of the Awlad Said tribe', '\"When climbing Jebel Um Shomer, the choice of accommodation may depend on several factors such as the duration of the climb, your itinerary, and weather conditions. Below are some common options for lodging when climbing Jebel Um Shomer:\r\n\r\nCamping: If you want to experience a close connection with nature, you can camp in suitable areas on the hillsides or at the foot of the mountain. This requires you to have appropriate camping gear and adhere to camping regulations and environmental protection guidelines.\r\n\r\nGuesthouses: Areas near the mountain often have guesthouses or basic lodging facilities available. This can be a convenient option if you prefer basic amenities and easy access from the mountain trail.\r\n\r\nHotels/Apartments: If you prefer a more comfortable lodging experience before and after the climb, you can choose hotels or apartments in nearby towns or tourist areas.\r\n\r\nOutdoor Tents: Some mountaineering organizations may provide outdoor tent rental services for travelers. This provides convenience and comfort for lodging before and after the climb.\r\n\r\nHomestays: In some cases, you may be invited to stay at local homestays or community lodges along the way to or from Jebel Um Shomer. This can be a great opportunity to experience local culture and meet local residents.\r\n\r\nNote that accommodation may need to be booked in advance, especially during peak tourist seasons. Research and make reservations in advance to ensure you have a safe and comfortable place to rest before and after climbing Jebel Um Shomer\"', '\"Dangers When Climbing Jebel Um Shomer:\r\n\r\nExtreme Weather: Jebel Um Shomer can experience rapidly changing weather conditions, including sudden storms, high winds, and extreme temperatures, posing a risk to climbers.\r\n\r\nAltitude Sickness: The high altitude of Jebel Um Shomer can cause altitude sickness, with symptoms such as headache, nausea, and fatigue, particularly for those not acclimatized to the elevation.\r\n\r\nRockfall: Loose rocks and unstable terrain on Jebel Um Shomer can lead to rockfall, posing a significant danger to climbers, especially in steep sections.\r\n\r\nAvalanches: Certain areas of Jebel Um Shomer may be prone to avalanches, particularly after heavy snowfall or during thaw periods, presenting a serious hazard to climbers.\r\n\r\nNavigation Challenges: Jebel Um Shomer\'s rugged terrain and complex topography can make navigation difficult, increasing the risk of climbers getting lost or disoriented.\r\n\r\nPhysical Exhaustion: Climbing Jebel Um Shomer requires significant physical exertion, and climbers may experience exhaustion or dehydration, particularly if they are not adequately prepared or hydrated.\r\n\r\nEquipment Failure: Malfunctioning or inadequate climbing equipment, such as ropes, harnesses, or crampons, can pose a danger to climbers on Jebel Um Shomer\'s challenging terrain.\r\n\r\nLack of Emergency Services: Remote locations on Jebel Um Shomer may mean limited access to emergency services, making it essential for climbers to be self-sufficient and prepared to deal with emergencies.\r\n\r\nWildlife Encounters: Jebel Um Shomer is home to various wildlife species, including snakes and scorpions, which can pose a risk of bites or stings to climbers.\r\n\r\nOverestimation of Abilities: Climbers may overestimate their abilities or underestimate the challenges of climbing Jebel Um Shomer, leading to accidents or injuries on the mountain.\r\n\r\nAwareness of these dangers and careful preparation are essential for climbers attempting to summit Jebel Um Shomer safely\"', 0),
(4, 'Yala Peak', '1.jpg', '\"Climb one of the few non-technical peaks in Nepal and experience the mighty Himalaya away from the crowds\r\n\r\n\"', '\"The summit of the peak is located at 5,500 m (18,000 ft) above sea level and it provides a vantage point from where Shishapangma , 8,013 m (26,289 ft), can be seen. The Tsergo Ri giant landslide occurred close to Yala Peak.\r\nThis peak is considered as a trekking peak by the Nepal Mountaineering Association, and is a relatively simple, non-technical climb. The climbing of Yala Peak passes through the Langtang National Park. The flora and fauna of the peak and surrounding area consist of Rhododendron, Snow leopard, and Red panda. In its first leg, climbers choose to go to Kyanjin Monastery 3,900 m (12,800 ft), a famous Buddhist pilgrimage place, to adjust to the altitude and climate. Once acclimatized, the climbers move towards the base camp at Yala Kharka 4,600 m (15,100 ft)\"', '\"Day pack with rain cover (35 litre +)\r\nRucksack or duffle bag (for the porters to carry your overnight kit)\r\nCLOTHES\r\nMountain environments are notoriously unpredictable. A layering system works best so that you can put on and remove items to adjust your temperature. You\'ll need to be equipped for all eventualities, although you won\'t necessarily need to use everything if you\'re lucky with the mountain conditions.\r\n\r\nWaterproof jacket (windproof)\r\n3- to 4-season down jacket, with hood\r\nWaterproof and windproof overtrousers\r\nLightweight trekking trousers\r\nThermals (top and bottom, wool or synthetic)\r\n2/3 trekking t-shirts/shirts\r\nFleece or warm mid-layer\r\nWarm gloves\r\nHiking socks and merino liners\r\nWoolly hat\r\nSun hat/cap\r\nSpare underwear\r\nBuff or similar\r\nSomething to sleep in\r\nSHOES\r\nWorn-in, waterproof hiking boots (with ankle support). While B1 boots (crampon compatible) are suitable for the climb, they are not good enough for extreme weather conditions. It is recommended to contact your host at least one month prior to your trip for specific guidance on the appropriate footwear. If you do not already have B2 boots and are thinking of purchasing them, climbing enthusiasts may find it beneficial to invest in B2 boots. However, if you prefer not to make the purchase, renting B2 boots in Kathmandu is also a viable option.\r\nLightweight trainers (for the evenings)\r\nFlip-flops or sandals\r\nSLEEPING\r\n4-season sleeping bag with hood (with a comfort rating down to around -20°c)\r\nSleeping bag liner (a good liner can add a few degrees extra warmth)\r\nPillowcase (optional)\r\nOTHER\r\nTrekking poles\r\nTravel towel\r\nSun protection and lip balm (high SPF: 50+)\r\nSunglasses (UV blocking, ideally with a \'wrap-around\' design)\r\n2 x 1-litre water bottles (metal SIGG bottles can double up as hot water bottles at night)\r\nHeadtorch (LED recommended)\r\nEarplugs (for the teahouses)\r\nFirst aid kit and/or personal medication\r\nWater purification tablets/system\r\nBiodegradable wet wipes\r\nHand gel\r\nSmall biodegradable bags to take toilet tissue off the mountain\r\nToilet paper/tissues\r\n1 x passport photos for trek permits\r\nPowerbank/solar charger\r\nUniversal plug adaptor\r\nBook/Kindle/cards for downtime\r\nPlease remove all unnecessary packing before you leave home and ensure you take all plastic off the mountain to be disposed of in Kathmandu.\"', '<iframe src=\"https://www.google.com/maps/embed?pb=!1m18!1m12!1m3!1d14061.196513445591!2d85.61770025006828!3d28.228599164199824!2m3!1f0!2f0!3f0!3m2!1i1024!2i768!4f13.1!3m3!1m2!1s0x39ea5fdf4b3f00e5%3A0x8f60a4cd99bc3d17!2sYala%20Peak!5e0!3m2!1sen!2s!4v1708606953443!5m2!1sen!2s\" width=\"600\" height=\"450\" style=\"border:0;\" allowfullscreen=\"\" loading=\"lazy\" referrerpolicy=\"no-referrer-when-downgrade\"></iframe>', 'Yala Peak is a mountain located in Nepal, near the Langtang region', '\"You’ll stay in a centrally located tourist hotel in the heart of Thamel (such as the Hotel Holy Himalaya, or one of a similar standard), close to the main shopping area and heritage sites. You will stay in twin-share rooms.                                                        ON THE TREK\r\nGenerally, most adventures to Nepal are based in remote areas where the accommodation will be basic. On the trek you will stay in teahouses most nights – these are mountain lodges that tend to have a communal dining area and basic toilets. The rooms are usually twin-share sorted by gender, however, if there is an odd number in the group they may occasionally be mixed. There’s no heating so you\'ll need your warm sleeping bag. WiFi and hot showers are often available at a small cost. You can usually charge your phone up – again, you guessed it, for a cost – so remember to take an adapter.\r\n\r\nYou\'ll also spend one night in a twin-share dome tent at Yala Peak Base Camp. All your camping kit is provided, but you might wish to pack a small inflatable pillow.\r\n\r\nUPGRADES\r\nFor solo travellers looking for their own space a private room can be booked, please see Optional Extras for pricing. Please note, this is only possible for the two nights in Kathmandu and is subject to availability. Please request this at the time of booking.\"', 'Yala Peak is an excellent starting point for Himalayan climbing without going about 6000m. It is also a good challenge for people who haven\'t been to altitude before as the ascent is gradual. For the peak itself previous winter walking / mountaineering skills such as using a walking axe and crampons is a bonus, but is not essential as the guides will offer training whilst you\'re trekking to the peak - you will have time to learn and practice the skills needed such as clipping into a rope and walking safely with the group.', 0),
(5, 'Fuji', '1.jpg', '\"Enjoy an unforgettable experience on this Prince Route Overnight Hike to climb Mount Fuji.\r\nMount Fuji, Japan\'s highest volcano at 3,776.24 meters (12,389 feet), stands proudly on the island of Honshu and attracts numerous visitors each year. Its status as one of Japan\'s three sacred peaks adds to its allure.\"', '\"Mount Fuji, also known as Fuji-san, is located on Honshu Island and is the highest mountain in Japan, standing at 3,776.24 meters above sea level. It is a dormant stratovolcano that last erupted in the years 1707-1708. Mount Fuji is situated approximately 100 km southwest of Tokyo and can be seen from the capital on a clear day. The mountain has a uniquely symmetrical cone shape and is snow-capped for about five months each year, serving as a symbol of the country and frequently depicted in artistic works, as well as being a popular destination for visitors from around the world to Japan.\r\n\r\nLegend has it that the renowned ascetic monk Hasegawa Kakugyo (1541–1646) climbed to the summit more than 100 times. His achievements led to the formation of Fuji-ko, a group of people who worship Mount Fuji.\r\n\r\nMount Fuji is one of Japan\'s \"\"Three Holy Mountains\"\" (三霊山, San reizan), along with Mount Haku and Mount Tate, recognized for its special scenic and historical significance. Mount Fuji was added to the UNESCO World Heritage List on June 22, 2013, for its cultural value. According to UNESCO, it has inspired artists and poets and has been a pilgrimage site for centuries.\"', '\"Mount Fuji (also known as Fuji-san) is one of Japan\'s cultural icons and geographical wonders. Standing at 3,776 meters, it is the highest peak in Japan, resulting from volcanic activity that began about 100,000 years ago.\r\n\r\nAs you prepare to conquer Mount Fuji, consider the following skills to ensure safety and success:\r\n\r\nForaging and finding clean water: During your climb, you need to know how to find safe food and drinking water.\r\nBuilding shelter: Create a shelter to protect yourself from harsh weather.\r\nMaking fire: Know how to start a fire to keep warm, cook food, and signal for help.\r\nNavigation and orientation: Use maps, compasses, or modern technology to determine the correct direction.\r\nFirst aid and treating minor injuries: Know how to administer first aid and treat injuries to prevent serious harm.\r\nRemember, climbing Mount Fuji requires thorough preparation in terms of health, climbing skills, and survival skills to ensure safety and success. Wishing you an exciting and memorable journey!\"', '<iframe src=\"https://www.google.com/maps/embed?pb=!1m18!1m12!1m3!1d13327562.152274204!2d119.21564464999999!3d35.360625500000005!2m3!1f0!2f0!3f0!3m2!1i1024!2i768!4f13.1!3m3!1m2!1s0x6019629a42fdc899%3A0xa6a1fcc916f3a4df!2sMount%20Fuji!5e0!3m2!1sen!2s!4v1708607560677!5m2!1sen!2s\" width=\"600\" height=\"450\" style=\"border:0;\" allowfullscreen=\"\" loading=\"lazy\" referrerpolicy=\"no-referrer-when-downgrade\"></iframe>', 'Kitayama, Fujinomiya, Shizuoka, Japan', '\"Fujisan Hongu Sengen Taisha Shrine: This is a popular starting point for climbers, with three of the four trails originating here. The shrine is also where you can purify yourself before tackling the mountain from the traditional starting point.\r\n\r\nAsagiri Plateau: Located on the west side of Mount Fuji, this vast highland is home to herds of cattle, making it a major dairy farming region. Walking along the plateau, you will encounter picturesque views of Mount Fuji reflected in lakes and ponds, with cows and goats grazing nearby. You can also participate in hands-on activities like milking cows and walking goats.\r\n\r\nShiraito Falls: Head to Shiraito Falls to witness an impressive wall of water cascading down into a large rocky base. The stream creates a spectrum of colors shifting between white and blue, with dense foliage above creating a scene of the waterfall immersed in a sea of green.\r\n\r\nFuji Safari Park: For animal lovers, visit Fuji Safari Park, where animals are given a spacious outdoor area resembling their natural habitat. Take a bus (or drive your own vehicle) to see giraffes, elephants, leopards, and lions living under the protection of Mount Fuji.\"', '\"Fujisan Hongu Sengen Taisha Shrine: This is a popular starting point for climbers, with three of the four trails beginning here. The shrine also offers a place for purification before embarking on the traditional ascent of the mountain.\r\n\r\nAsagiri Plateau: Located to the west of Mount Fuji, this vast highland area is home to herds of cattle, making it a significant dairy farming region. Walking along the plateau, you\'ll encounter picturesque views of Mount Fuji reflected in lakes and ponds, with cows and goats grazing nearby. You can also engage in hands-on activities like milking cows and walking goats.\r\n\r\nShiraito Falls: Visit Shiraito Falls to marvel at an impressive wall of water cascading down a large rock face. The waterfall creates a spectrum of white to blue hues against the dense greenery above, offering a breathtaking scene of cascading water amidst a sea of green.\r\n\r\nFuji Safari Park: For animal lovers, a visit to Fuji Safari Park is a must, where animals are given a spacious outdoor environment similar to their natural habitats. Take a bus (or drive your own vehicle) to see giraffes, elephants, leopards, and lions living under the watchful eye of Mount Fuji.\"', 0),
(6, 'Kazbek', '1.jpg', '\"Clamber to the summit of the visually stunning Mount Kazbek – a dormant stratovolcano made from hardened lava\r\n\r\nTackle a challenging trek through the wilderness and across the hiker’s paradise of the Kazbegi National Park\r\n\r\nFollow a less-travelled route into the Caucasus, including steep ascents, glacier crossings and an epic final climb\r\n\r\nStay at the cosy and comfortable Altihut (3014m), Georgia\'s first environmentally friendly alpine-style mountain refuge\"', '\"Mount Kazbek, also known as Mount Kazbegi, is a dormant volcano and one of the significant mountains of the Caucasus range, located in Georgia, just south of the border with Russia. With an elevation of 5,054 meters (16,581 feet) above sea level, Mount Kazbek is the highest peak in Eastern Georgia. It is also the country\'s third-highest mountain (after Mount Shkhara and Mount Janga). Kazbek is the second-highest volcano in the Caucasus, only after Mount Elbrus. The peak lies just west of the town of Stepantsminda and is the most prominent geographical feature in the area.\r\n\r\nThe name Kazbek is subject to controversy; some believe it was named after a Circassian noble who lived on it, while others think it was named after the local noble Dimitri Chopikashvili (the grandfather of the Georgian writer Aleksandre Kazbegi) who received the title \"\"Kazbeg\"\" from the Georgian king Erekle II. The word \"\"Kazbek\"\" means \"\"noble\"\" in Kabardian. This title appeared during the reign of the Georgian king Rostom in the 17th century. The name of the mountain in Georgian, Mqinvartsveri, translates to \"\"Ice Peak\"\" or \"\"Frozen Peak\"\" in English.\r\n\r\nMount Kazbek is located on the Khokh range, a range running north of the Greater Caucasus mountain range, and is traversed by the gorges of the Ardon and Terek rivers. At its eastern foot runs the Georgian Military Road through the Darial Pass, which is 2,378 meters (7,805 feet) high. The mountain itself lies along the edge of the Borjomi-Kazbegi Fault Line (a northern part of the North Anatolian Fault). The area is geologically active, with many small earthquakes occurring regularly. An active hot water system/hot springs also surround the mountain. Kazbek is a potential volcano, built from trachyte and covered by lava, and has the shape of a double cone, with its base at an elevation of 1,770 meters (5,800 feet). Due to the steepness of its slopes, the glaciers of Kazbek are not very large.\"', 'This trek is suitable for experienced hikers, although no previous technical mountaineering experience is required. You\'ll need to muster a high level of mental and physical strength to summit this 5054m peak, so a good level of fitness is required. This trek is suitable for those who exercise regularly and who have some recent prior experience of multi-day hiking, and ideally trekking at altitude. The summit day is a long and tough day involving approximately 11 hours of trekking and 1400m of ascent and 2040m of descent. You must come prepared for the cold on summit day, and with suitable equipment to deal with this. Although the route has been designed with acclimatisation in mind, the thin air at these altitudes will make this feel tougher. In terms of terrain, you will be walking on some narrow rocky trails and on snow and ice - crampons will be needed on multiple days of the trek. It\'s very important you bring or hire the correct equipment. You\'ll be roped up for the glacier traverse and the summit attempt for safety, as well as during any adverse weather. Your guide will provide some basic training on aspects such as the use of crampons, ice axes and walking in a rope team prior to the ascent.', '<iframe src=\"https://www.google.com/maps/embed?pb=!1m18!1m12!1m3!1d11729.32303769085!2d44.504612861267944!3d42.69671673861376!2m3!1f0!2f0!3f0!3m2!1i1024!2i768!4f13.1!3m3!1m2!1s0x405acbde6f644593%3A0xa0708b3c7d5fb28c!2sMt%20Kazbek!5e0!3m2!1sen!2s!4v1708607685474!5m2!1sen!2s\" width=\"600\" height=\"450\" style=\"border:0;\" allowfullscreen=\"\" loading=\"lazy\" referrerpolicy=\"no-referrer-when-downgrade\"></iframe>', 'Mt Kazbek, Georgia', 'You\'ll stay in two mountain refuges - the Altihut (3014m) and Meteo Station (3653m.) The Altihut is newly built and offers simple, clean and comfortable accommodation serving hearty Georgian meals. There is heating and running water but showers are not currently available. Meteo Station meanwhile is a very basic high-altitude hut from the Soviet era and there is no running water here. Both nights will be in mixed dorms.', '\"Mount Kazbek is not an easy mountain to conquer. Here are some dangers and challenges climbers face when attempting Kazbek:\r\n\r\n Altitude: With an elevation of 5,054 meters (16,581 feet), Kazbek is a high mountain, and reaching the summit requires thorough preparation and good physical condition.\r\n Harsh Climate: The Caucasus region has a harsh climate with rapidly changing weather conditions. Climbers must face strong winds, snowfall, and cold weather.\r\n Climbing Routes: The route to the summit of Kazbek is not easy. It involves crossing rocky segments, ice, and challenging terrain.\r\n Risk of Rockfall: Kazbek is a dormant volcano, so there is a risk of rockfall and eruptions. Climbers must be careful to avoid dangerous areas.\r\n Human Factor: Climbing depends not only on physical strength and technique but also on cooperation and support from teammates and guides.\r\n\r\nRemember that mountain climbing is a daunting challenge, and participants need to be well-prepared and patient. Always adhere to safety rules and respect nature while undertaking this journey.\"', 0),
(7, 'Mount Rinjani', '1.jpg', 'Mount Rinjani, or Gunung Rinjani, is an active volcano in Indonesia on the island of Lombok. It stands at 3,726 meters and is the second highest volcano in Indonesia. Trekking Mount Rinjani offers a completely unique experience for nature lovers.', '\"The oldest recorded historical eruption was in 1847. Previous to that this was a very remote region indeed, hence the lack of records.\r\n\r\nThere was a spate of activity from 1994 to 1995 which resulted in the further growth of the crater cone Gunung Baru, since renamed Gunung Barujari (Finger Mountain).\r\n\r\nOn 27 April 2009 Gunung Barujari became active again with that activity continuing through to May 2009. The summit ascent routes were closed at that time as the eruptions intensified with plumes of smoke and ash as high as 8,000 m. A Volcanic Explosivity Index (VEI):2 rating was issued for the activity between May and December 2009. The ascent routes re-opened on September 14th 2009 but hiking routes down into the crater lake were still deemed unsafe and remained closed.\r\n\r\nIn February 2010 observers at the Gunung Rinjani Observation Post detected a smoke plume that rose 100 m from the volcano. The activity in early 2010 is centred about Gunung Barujari. On May 1st 2010 a column of smoke was again observed rising from Rinjani issuing eruptions 1,300-1,600 metres tall with thick brown color and strong pressure. On May 5th 2010 a possible ash plume rose to an altitude of 5.5 km (18,000 ft) and drifted 150 km NW. Accordingly the Center of Volcanology and Geological Hazard Mitigation advised that intermittent activity could produce ash plumes to 1,500 m (5,000 ft) above the caldera. In light of this The Volcanic Explosivity Index Alert Level was raised to 2 with a recommendation that there be no activity within a radius of 4 km from the eruption at Gunung Barujari.\"', 'Hiking boots or trekking shoes are absolutely essential as they are waterproof, along with a windproof jacket and a headlamp. If you are about to summit, the use of Poles (sticks) is highly recommended to navigate over the boulders above. At 2000m, you will feel as if you are no longer in the tropics because humidity increases, heat loss, and the temperature can drop. If clothing becomes damp and is not suitable, it will be harder when temperatures drop to the freezing point at the summit, often accompanied by cold winds.', '<iframe src=\"https://www.google.com/maps/embed?pb=!1m18!1m12!1m3!1d31575.215369052126!2d116.41837961855752!3d-8.411293132336997!2m3!1f0!2f0!3f0!3m2!1i1024!2i768!4f13.1!3m3!1m2!1s0x2dcc2d800216cccf%3A0x3c03cdbf11d30a1e!2sMount%20Rinjani!5e0!3m2!1sen!2s!4v1708607848586!5m2!1sen!2s\" width=\"600\" height=\"450\" style=\"border:0;\" allowfullscreen=\"\" loading=\"lazy\" referrerpolicy=\"no-referrer-when-downgrade\"></iframe>', 'Sembalun Lawang, Sembalun, East Lombok Regency, West Nusa Tenggara, Indonesia', 'Besides the summit of Mount Rinjani, another popular destination for visitors is \"Lake Segara Anak,\" a crater lake situated at an altitude of 2,000 meters above sea level. To reach this location, one can trek from Senaru village, which is 600 meters above sea level, or from Sembalun Lawang village, at an elevation of 1,150 meters above sea level. At the lake, you can camp, fish, and the residents of Lombok traditionally visit Lake Segara Anak to bathe in the outdoor hot springs and fish.', '\"Mount Rinjani is a challenging and relatively dangerous destination. Here are some points to note:\r\n\r\nAltitude: With an elevation of 3,726 meters (12,224 feet) above sea level, climbing Mount Rinjani requires good preparation and physical fitness. The change in altitude can cause oxygen scarcity and breathlessness.\r\n\r\nHarsh Terrain: Mount Rinjani features diverse terrains, from tropical forests to volcanic peaks. This requires overcoming crevices, scree, and steep paths.\r\n\r\nUnstable Weather: The weather on Mount Rinjani can change rapidly. Be prepared for rain, wind, and cold conditions.\r\n\r\nThe Risks of Climbing: Climbing always carries risks such as rockfalls, accidents, and sudden weather changes. This requires climbing skills and vigilance.\r\n\r\nIf you plan to explore Mount Rinjani, prepare thoroughly, follow the guide\'s instructions, and ensure your safety.\"', 0),
(8, 'Fansipan', '1.jpg', 'Fansipan is the highest peak in Vietnam, located in the Hoang Lien Son mountain range in the Northwest region of Vietnam. The mountain stands at an absolute height of 3,147.3 meters. Fansipan is also the highest peak in the Indochina Peninsula and is known as the \"Roof of Indochina.\"', '\"Fansipan, also known as Phan Xi Păng, is a majestic mountain in Vietnam. Let me share some fascinating details about this remarkable peak:\r\n\r\nHeight and Nickname:\r\nFansipan stands at an impressive 3,147.3 meters (10,326 feet) above sea level. It is the highest mountain on the Indochinese peninsula, which includes Vietnam, Laos, and Cambodia. No wonder it’s affectionately called \"\"the Roof of Indochina\"\".\r\nIts elevation was initially recorded as 3,143 meters (10,312 feet) in 1909 but has since been updated to the current height.\r\nGeography and Formation:\r\nFansipan is part of the Hoang Lien Son mountain range and is situated on the border of Lào Cai and Lai Châu provinces in Vietnam.\r\nThe mountain’s formation dates back a staggering 250–260 million years. It emerged during the transition from the Permian period (Paleozoic era) to the Triassic period (Mesozoic era).\r\nThe Himalayan orogeny during the Late Mesozoic further uplifted Fansipan and the entire Hoang Lien Son range. This geological process also created the Red River Fault to the east12.\r\nName Origins:\r\nThe origin of the name Phan Xi Păng remains somewhat mysterious. The most widely accepted theory suggests that it evolved from Hủa Xi Pan, a local name based on the mountain’s shape.\r\nAnother theory attributes the name to the Hmong people, who referred to it as the “azalea mountain” due to the abundance of azaleas and other Rhododendron species.\r\nInterestingly, there’s a suggestion that the name might have originated from Phạm Thị Phương Quế, a geography official during the Nguyễn dynasty who helped map the area and define the border with China in 1905. Local pronunciation variations eventually led to Phan Xi Păng.\r\nSummit Mark:\r\nAt the mountain’s peak, an initial metal pyramid was installed by Soviet engineers from Hòa Bình province in 1985. This amateur mountaineering expedition marked the first ascent since the colonial period and coincided with the 40th anniversary of Victory Day of the Soviet Union over Nazi Germany.\r\nClimbing Fansipan:\r\nFansipan can be conquered through a steep and fairly strenuous hike. In the past, it took about 5–6 days to reach the summit and return from Sa Pa.\r\nNowadays, a cable car provides an alternative route for those seeking a less arduous ascent.\r\nFansipan’s rich history, geological significance, and breathtaking views make it a must-visit destination for adventurers and nature enthusiasts\"', '\" For a long trek like Fansipan, preparing necessary items to bring along will help you save costs. It also makes you more proactive in handling situations. The items you should bring include:\r\n\r\n Health and spirit: The prerequisite factor for your trip. Ensure that your physical condition is good enough to withstand the weather impacts or obstacles on a journey that can last for hours. Before the day of the mountain climb, you can perform light, simple exercises to strengthen your health.\r\n  A large backpack with supportive straps: A backpack is always the most suitable and compact choice to carry items when climbing. Supportive straps will help reduce some of the burden throughout the movement.\r\n\r\n Choosing appropriate clothing and outfits: Depending on the time you go trekking in Sapa, you can choose suitable outfits. If climbing Fansipan from May to September, you should prioritize wearing cool T-shirts and wide-leg pants with good sweat-absorbent material. Don\'t forget to prepare a thin jacket as well.\"', '<iframe src=\"https://www.google.com/maps/embed?pb=!1m18!1m12!1m3!1d14765.32247344102!2d103.76470024668507!3d22.303332624947103!2m3!1f0!2f0!3f0!3m2!1i1024!2i768!4f13.1!3m3!1m2!1s0x36cd448786c84543%3A0x98e9595d4892bc5a!2sFansipan!5e0!3m2!1sen!2s!4v1708607983636!5m2!1sen!2s\" width=\"600\" height=\"450\" style=\"border:0;\" allowfullscreen=\"\" loading=\"lazy\" referrerpolicy=\"no-referrer-when-downgrade\"></iframe>', 'Fansipan\r\nTam Đường District, Lai Chau', 'A very small village situated at an altitude of about 1,500 m (4,920 ft), which provides accommodation and food. Further up, at an altitude of 2,800 m (9,190 ft), there is an overnight camp. Most booked trips include the use of these amenities in their price if they are requested.', 'Fansipan attracts climbers year-round, from hot sunny days to cold snowy days. Each weather condition presents its own set of challenges and attractions, but for those who are not professional climbers, it is advisable to avoid the rainy season and days that are excessively cold. Climbing Fansipan involves navigating through rugged mountainous terrain with steep slopes of 70 to 80 degrees, which can become very dangerous if rain makes the rocks slippery. And since it is at an altitude of 3,143m, the climate on Fansipan can be quite harsh, especially at night, so it is also necessary to avoid days that are too cold in case the body cannot withstand it.', 0),
(9, 'Phongan Razi', '1.jpg', '\"Although not well known yet Myanmar has lots to offer for mountaineers, climbers and trekkers. You will be among the first travelers trekking these remote trails.\r\nDiscovery DMC and Trekking Myanmar team has been organizing treks to some of the most remote corners of the country for well over 10 years. Most of these are still not in guide books and destinations remain untouched and unique.\"', '\"Kachin State, located in the northern most part, is one of the seven States of the Union of Myanmar. Lies between China to the east and India to the west, and has a land area of 34,379.22 square miles.\r\nGeography: – Kachin State is part of the eastern edge of the Himalayan Range and is also continuous with the Yunnan escarpment, composing the Tibet-Myanmar frontier mountain ranges. Hkakaborazi, the highest mountain in South East Asia at 19 315 feet, and Indawgyi, the largest lake in Myanmar with 98 square miles, are all located in Kachin State.\"', 'Hiking boots or trekking shoes are absolutely essential as they are waterproof, along with a windproof jacket and a headlamp. If you are about to summit, the use of Poles (sticks) is highly recommended to navigate over the boulders above. At 2000m, you will feel as if you are no longer in the tropics because humidity increases, heat loss, and the temperature can drop. If clothing becomes damp and is not suitable, it will be harder when temperatures drop to the freezing point at the summit, often accompanied by cold winds.', '<iframe src=\"https://www.google.com/maps/embed?pb=!1m18!1m12!1m3!1d3538.756578346636!2d96.93277147511137!3d27.50794487629745!2m3!1f0!2f0!3f0!3m2!1i1024!2i768!4f13.1!3m3!1m2!1s0x373c5b40c17b1a59%3A0x3ffa719b071958ed!2sPhongan%20Razi!5e0!3m2!1sen!2s!4v1708608639712!5m2!1sen!2s\" width=\"600\" height=\"450\" style=\"border:0;\" allowfullscreen=\"\" loading=\"lazy\" referrerpolicy=\"no-referrer-when-downgrade\"></iframe>', 'Phongan Razi, ပူတာအို, Myanmar (Burma)', 'Ziyadum, located at 1080 meter above sea. At first we cross Namro creek to Awadum I, mainly inhabited by Lisu and separate in to two by a large paddy field. From here we walk pass vast paddy field to Awadum II, from here the trail goes through lush evergreen forests and enjoyable scenery towards Ziyadum. Ziyadum is the most northwestern and last frontier village in Putao region, mainly resident are Rawang tribes', 'Trek route will be a challenging one with narrow line however beautiful pine elevation with moist upper deciduous forest yet fill with Rhododendron make the scenery impressive. There are three different camp sites on snow line and we will find right spot for camping according to the snowfall. Tonight we will have to prepare for cold weather as temperature could be freezing during the night', 0),
(10, 'K2', '1.jpg', 'K2 (also known as Mount Godwin-Austen, Lambha Pahar, Chogori, Kechu, or Dapsang), standing at 8,611 m (28,251 ft), is the second-highest peak on Earth, located on the border between Taxkorgan County in Kashgar Prefecture, Xinjiang, China, and Pakistan, within the Karakoram mountain range.', '\"The name K2 originates from the Great Trigonometrical Survey of British India. Thomas Montgomerie conducted the first survey of the Karakoram range from Mount Haramukh, about 210 km (130 miles) away, and identified the two highest peaks, naming them K1 and K2.\r\n\r\nThe policy of the Great Survey was to use local names for mountains whenever possible, hence K1 became known as Masherbrum. However, K2, being so remote, had no known local name. The mountain cannot be seen from Askole, the last village to the south, nor from the nearest settlement to the north. K2 is only slightly visible from the end of the Baltoro Glacier, far beyond the reach of most observers. The name Chogori, deriving from the Balti words chhogo (\"\"big\"\") and ri (\"\"mountain\"\") , has been suggested as a local name but there is no evidence that the name Chogori is widely used. This name might originate from Western explorers, or as a facetious answer to the question \"\"What is that mountain called?\"\". Other names such as Dapsang, Lambha Pahar, etc., also exist but are not widely used.\r\n\r\nLacking a local name, the name Godwin-Austen has been used to honor Henry Godwin-Austen, an early explorer of the area. Although this name was rejected by the Royal Geographical Society, it still appears on some maps and continues to be referenced today.\"', '\"Climbing K2 requires extensive preparation and training. Climbers need to be physically and mentally prepared for the challenge, as the climbing process can take several weeks and requires extreme physical effort.\r\n\r\nClimbers also need to bring specialized equipment, including ice axes, crampons, and ropes, and they must be proficient in using them.\r\n\r\nAdditionally, climbers need to familiarize themselves with the mountain\'s weather patterns and bring enough food and water to maintain their health throughout the climb.\"', '<iframe src=\"https://www.google.com/maps/embed?pb=!1m18!1m12!1m3!1d12930.943900521544!2d76.50480035549764!3d35.87998656037615!2m3!1f0!2f0!3f0!3m2!1i1024!2i768!4f13.1!3m3!1m2!1s0x38fad5add7ff4adb%3A0xc531647bf8e9d577!2sK2!5e0!3m2!1sen!2s!4v1708608839019!5m2!1sen!2s\" width=\"600\" height=\"450\" style=\"border:0;\" allowfullscreen=\"\" loading=\"lazy\" referrerpolicy=\"no-referrer-when-downgrade\"></iframe>', 'k2, china', 'There are no shelters, only tents can be pitched for refuge.', 'K2 is known as the \"Savage Mountain\" because of its brutal ascent. With the second-highest fatality rate among mountains over 8000 meters, one in every four climbers who reach the summit dies, with an official count of 77 deaths in 300 successful ascents. Because ascending from the China side is more dangerous and difficult, most climbers choose the route from Pakistan. Unlike Annapurna, the mountain with the highest fatality rate (191 ascents and 61 deaths), or any other mountain above 8000 meters, no one has ever climbed K2 in winter.', 0),
(11, 'Nanga Parbat', '1.jpg', 'Nanga Parbat (The Naked Mountain), standing at 8,126 meters (26,660 ft), is the world\'s ninth-highest mountain. The mountain is located on the western side of the Himalayas in the Gilgit-Baltistan region of Pakistan.', '\"\r\nNanga Parbat was first successfully climbed in 1953 by a joint expedition of Austrian and German climbers. This was the first successful ascent of any peak over 8,000 meters.\r\n\r\nNanga Parbat is a stark mountain. It is unapologetic, not shy. It is always hungry, devouring anything within its reach.\r\n\r\nHermann Buhl, an Austrian climber, was the first person to ascend the south face of Nanga Parbat in 1953. However, the mountain has a darker history. Many climbers have perished trying to climb the Killer Mountain, including the famous climber Hermann Buhl in 1957.\"', '\"Climbing Nanga Parbat requires extensive preparation and training. Climbers need to be physically and mentally prepared for the challenge, as the climbing process can take several weeks and requires extreme physical effort.\r\n\r\nClimbers also need to bring specialized equipment, including ice axes, crampons, and ropes, and they must be proficient in using them.\r\n\r\nAdditionally, climbers need to familiarize themselves with the mountain\'s weather patterns and bring enough food and water to maintain their health throughout the climb.\"', '<iframe src=\"https://www.google.com/maps/embed?pb=!1m18!1m12!1m3!1d13035.01447006242!2d74.5788448549978!3d35.237502863735635!2m3!1f0!2f0!3f0!3m2!1i1024!2i768!4f13.1!3m3!1m2!1s0x38e6c007399ee885%3A0x10e2393cfebe6c2!2sNanga%20Parbat!5e0!3m2!1sen!2s!4v1708608947775!5m2!1sen!2s\" width=\"600\" height=\"450\" style=\"border:0;\" allowfullscreen=\"\" loading=\"lazy\" referrerpolicy=\"no-referrer-when-downgrade\"></iframe>', 'Nanga Parbat, Pakistan', 'This mountain is also known for its steep slopes, making it one of the most difficult peaks to climb. The area around the mountain is home to several indigenous communities, including the Diamer and Kohistan tribes.', 'Climbing Nanga Parbat is not for the faint-hearted. This mountain has claimed the lives of many experienced climbers, and it requires high levels of skill and experience to successfully conquer. The climb involves crossing dangerous glaciers, navigating steep ice walls, and climbing over perilous rock formations. The weather on the mountain is also unpredictable and can change rapidly, making it even more challenging for climbers.', 0);
